body:
@juliencarponcy, thanks for reporting this!

Reason is that the estimators seem to have moved to other folders, e.g., `CNNClassifier` is now in `sktime.classification.deep_learning`.

A full repository search should reveal where the classes have moved to, so this is a good first issue!

There is a "hard version" of this, which is writing a test that checks that all links in the API reference are alive (but that can be a separate work item).

body: I'll be happy to solve this issue out but I can't find where this issue is coming from. I looked up here: https://github.com/sktime/sktime/tree/main/docs/source/api_reference but couldn't find anything.

Oops, seemed like I missed this mention of me. Apologies.

@GigaMoksh thanks for considering taking this up. I looked around and found the source of the problem.

These HTML files are made automatically via `sphinx`. I encourage you to look into the `/docs` directory and read more about how documentation in `sktime` is structured. [Here's](https://www.sktime.org/en/stable/developer_guide/documentation.html) a developer guide for documentation prescribed to contributors. If you have any further doubts (eg: need further resources), you could visit slack / discord and ask on the relevant channel(s).

You can try to solve it on your own if you want to, but here's the problem and solution:
<details>

In `docs/source/api_reference/classification.rst`, relevant lines for the `deep_learning` submodule are missing. This is why `autosummary` directive is failing to produce files for any estimator under this submodule. 

The solution is simple, add the missing lines and one could take other submodules as reference. As an additional step, one could also try if find if any other submodules are missing in any other `.rst` files.

</details>

Happy debugging!
thankyou @achieveordie! Will try to solve this issue asap.

from discussion on slack:

> While solving this issue: https://github.com/sktime/sktime/issues/3314  I encountered there isn't any network  module in docs/source/api_reference/ . How should I address this?

You could add a new file, simply, in the `api_reference` folder that follows the pattern, if that makes sense. If you do that, you should also make sure you add a link in the higher-level page, `source/api_reference.rst`.

That's how I interpret what @achieveordie has said above.

#### Reference Issues/PRs
Fixes #3314

#### What does this implement/fix? Explain your changes.
Added submodules `deep_learning`, `distance_based` and `kernel_based` in `regression.rst` and submodules `early_classification` and `deep_learning` in `classification.rst`

#### Does your contribution introduce a new dependency? If yes, which one?
No

#### What should a reviewer concentrate their feedback on?
To check if all submodules in `regression.rst` and `classification.rst` are added

##### For all contributions
- [x] I've added myself to the [list of contributors](https://github.com/sktime/sktime/blob/main/.all-contributorsrc).
- [ ] Optionally, I've updated sktime's [CODEOWNERS](https://github.com/sktime/sktime/blob/main/CODEOWNERS) to receive notifications about future changes to these files.
- [ ] I've added unit tests and made sure they pass locally.
